"|\u25cf\n|style=\"background:lightgreen; text-align:center\"|\uff5c\n|{{BJS stations|Tongzhou Beiyuan}}\n|{{large|{{lang|zh-cn|\u901a\u5dde\u5317\u82d1}}}}\n|\n|{{small|316 317 322 372 591 615 647 666 667 668 804 805 806 808 809 810 811 924 938 \u591c27}}\n|0:20\n|1.700\n|12.361\n|align=center rowspan=8|[[Tongzhou District, Beijing|Tongzhou]]\n|-\n|style=\"background:#{{BJS color|Batong}}; color:white\"|BT09\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u25cf\n|style=\"background:pink; text-align:center\"|\u25cf\n|style=\"background:lightgreen; text-align:center\"|\u25cf\n|{{BJS stations|Guo Yuan}}\n|{{large|{{lang|zh-cn|\u679c\u56ed}}}}\n|\n|{{small|312 316 317 552 591 668 805 938 \u591c29}}\n|0:23\n|1.465\n|13.826\n|-\n|style=\"background:#{{BJS color|Batong}}; color:white\"|BT10\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u25cf\n|style=\"background:pink; text-align:center\"|\uff5c\n|style=\"background:lightgreen; text-align:center\"|\u25cf\n|{{BJS stations|Jiu Ke Shu}}\n|{{large|{{lang|zh-cn|\u4e5d\u68f5\u6811}}}}\n|\n|{{small|372 582 587 668 805 810 938}}\n|0:25\n|0.990\n|14.816\n|-\n|style=\"background:#{{BJS color|Batong}}; color:white\"|BT11\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u25cf\n|style=\"background:pink; text-align:center\"|\uff5c\n|style=\"background:lightgreen; text-align:center\"|\u25cf\n|{{BJS stations|Li Yuan}}\n|{{large|{{lang|zh-cn|\u68a8\u56ed}}}}\n|\n|{{small|372 587 589 647 668 805 806 810 938}}\n|0:28\n|1.225\n|16.041\n|-\n|style=\"background:#{{BJS color|Batong}}; color:white\"|BT12\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u25cf\n|style=\"background:pink; text-align:center\"|\uff5c\n|style=\"background:lightgreen; text-align:center\"|\u25cf\n|{{BJS stations|Lin He Li}}\n|{{large|{{lang|zh-cn|\u4e34\u6cb3\u91cc}}}}\n|\n|{{small|435 587 589 806 810 924 938 \u4e13173 \u4e13203}}\n|0:30\n|1.257\n|17.298\n|-\n|style=\"background:#{{BJS color|Batong}}; color:white\"|BT13\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u25cf\n|style=\"background:pink; text-align:center\"|\uff5c\n|style=\"background:lightgreen; text-align:center\"|\u25cf\n|{{BJS stations|Tu Qiao}}\n|{{large|{{lang|zh-cn|\u571f\u6865}}}}\n|\n|{{small|435 591 805 806 807 810 910 924 938}}\n|0:32\n|0.776\n|18.074\n|-\n|style=\"background:#{{BJS color|Batong}}; color:white\"|\u2014{{efn|name=A|No official station codes are given after 2007.}}\n|style=\"text-align:center;\"|\u25cf\n|style=\"background:pink; text-align:center\"|\u25cf\n|style=\"background:lightgreen; text-align:center\"|\u25cf\n|{{BJS stations|Hua Zhuang}}\n|{{large|{{lang|zh-cn|\u82b1\u5e84}}}}\n|{{rint|beijing|7}}\n|\n|0:38\n|2.3\n|20.3\n|- bgcolor=\"lightgrey\"\n|style=\"background:#{{BJS color|Batong}}; color:white\"|\u2014{{efn|name=A|}}\n|\n|\n|\n|''{{BJS stations|Universal Resort}}''\n|{{large|{{lang|zh-cn|\u73af\u7403\u5ea6\u5047\u533a}}}}\n|{{rint|beijing|7}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|- style = \"background:#{{BJS color|Batong}}; height: 2pt\"\n| colspan=\"12\" |\n|}\n{{notelist}}\n\n[[Image:\u5317\u4eac\u516b\u901a\u7dda\u5217\u8eca\u8eca\u982d.JPG|thumb|180px|right|A Batong Line train at Sihui]]\n[[File:Beijing Subway Gaobeidian LineBT.jpg|thumb|180px|[[Gaobeidian station]] on the Ba Tong Line is located in the median of the [[Jingtong Expressway|Beijing-Tongzhou Expressway]]]]\n\n==Rolling stock==\n{{main|Beijing Subway Rolling Stock}}\n\nThe line uses 6-car Type B rolling stock.\n\n===Current===\n*[[Beijing Subway SFM01/07 train|SFM01 trainsets]] #TQ401-TQ408, #TQ414-TQ424\n*[[Beijing Subway SFM02 train|SFM02 trainsets]] #TQ409-TQ413\n*[[Beijing Subway SFM01/07 train|SFM07 trainsets]] #TQ425-TQ430\n*[[Beijing Subway BDK06 train|BDK06 trainsets]] #TQ431-TQ437\n\n===Former===\n*[[Beijing Subway DK3 train|DK3 trainsets]] #TQ101-TQ114\n*[[Beijing Subway DK16 train|DK16 trainsets]] #TQ115-TQ118\n\n==History==\n===Phase 1===\nConstruction of the Ba Tong Line began on December 28, 2001 and the line opened on December 27, 2003.\n\nIn 2012, traffic on Ba Tong Line was relieved by the opening of the parallel [[Line 6, Beijing Subway|Line 6]], with a 12.14% decrease in daily ridership and a 10\u201320% reduction in flow during rush hour.<ref name=\"ridership\">{{cite news|url=http://www.bjjtw.gov.cn/gzdt/ywsds/201302/t20130207_71407.htm |script-title=zh:\u6211\u5e02\u8f68\u9053\u4ea4\u901a\u7f51\u7edc\u5316\u8fd0\u8425\u6548\u679c\u51f8\u663e|date=2013-02-07|accessdate=2013-09-15|publisher=\u5317\u4eac\u5e02\u4ea4\u901a\u59d4\u5458\u4f1a [Beijing Municipal Transportation Committee] |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140109144501/http://www.bjjtw.gov.cn/gzdt/ywsds/201302/t20130207_71407.htm|archivedate=2014-01-09}}</ref> However, during peak hours sections the line still operates above 100% capacity.<ref name = \"ridership\"/>\n\n===Southern extension (Phase 2)===\nThere are 2 stations on the southern extension: {{BJS stations|Huazhuang}} station and {{BJS stations|Universal Resort}} station (both are transfer stations with the eastern extension of [[Line 7 (Beijing Subway)|Line 7]]).<ref>http://www.xinhuanet.com/local/2018-12/15/c_1123856864.htm</ref> The extension is 4.5&nbsp;km in length,<ref name=bj2019length>{{cite web|url=http://www.bjnews.com.cn/feature/2019/09/10/624954.html|title=\u5730\u94c17\u53f7\u7ebf\u4e1c\u5ef6\u3001\u516b\u901a\u7ebf\u5357\u5ef6\u4eca\u65e5\u8bd5\u8fd0\u884c \u5e74\u5e95\u5f00\u901a|date=2019-09-10}}</ref> including 3.8&nbsp;km underground section.<ref name=bj20181215>http://bj.people.com.cn/n2/2018/1215/c82840-32413471.html</ref> {{BJS stations|Huazhuang}} station was opened on December 28, 2019.<ref name=bjd-1/> {{BJS stations|Universal Resort}} station will open simultaneously with the opening of [[Universal Beijing Resort]]<ref name=bjd-0 /> (in May 2021<ref name=\"news202002\">{{Cite web|url=http://news.ifeng.com/c/7u78Lx2rAEY|title=\u5317\u4eac\u73af\u7403\u4e3b\u9898\u516c\u56ed\u660e\u5e745\u6708\u5f00\u56ed|date=2020-02-16|accessdate=2020-02-17}}</ref>).\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" cellpadding=\"3\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; text-align: right;\"\n!Segment!!Commencement!!Length!!Station(s)!!Name\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"| Sihui \u2014 Tuqiao\n| 27 December 2003\n| {{convert|18.964|km|mi|1|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.sina.com.cn/o/2003-05-29/2023169473s.shtml|date=2003-05-29|title=\u5317\u4eac\u5730\u94c1\u516b\u901a\u7ebf\u8f68\u9053\u5168\u7ebf\u8d2f\u901a \u4ecd\u5c06\u786e\u4fdd\u5e74\u5e95\u901a\u8f66}}</ref>\n| 13\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"| Phase 1\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"| Tuqiao \u2014 Hua Zhuang\n| 28 December 2019<ref name=bjd-1>{{cite web|url=http://bjwb.bjd.com.cn/html/2019-12/25/content_12438029.htm|title=7\u53f7\u7ebf\u4e1c\u5ef6\u516b\u901a\u7ebf\u5357\u5ef6\u672c\u5468\u516d\u5f00\u901a\u8bd5\u8fd0\u8425 \u8fd0\u8425\u65f6\u95f4\u4fdd\u6301\u4e0d\u53d8 \u73af\u7403\u5ea6\u5047\u533a\u7ad9\u6682\u4e0d\u5f00\u901a|date=2019-12-25}}</ref>\n|rowspan=\"2\"|{{convert|4.5|km|mi|abbr=on}}<ref name=bj2019length />\n| 1\n|rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: left;\"| Phase 2 (Southern extension)\n|-bgcolor=\"lightgrey\"\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"| Hua Zhuang \u2014 Universal Resort\n| 2021 (Planned)<ref name=bjd-0>{{cite web|url=http://www.bjd.com.cn/a/201912/24/WS5e01d31ce4b0e6e58393462e.html|title=\u5730\u94c17\u53f7\u7ebf\u4e1c\u5ef6\u3001\u516b\u901a\u7ebf\u5357\u5ef6\u5c06\u4e8e\u5e74\u5e95\u5f00\u901a\u8bd5\u8fd0\u8425|date=2019-12-24|quote=\u73af\u7403\u5ea6\u5047\u533a\u7ad9\u5c06\u968f\u73af\u7403\u5ea6\u5047\u533a\u5f00\u653e\u540c\u6b65\u8fd0\u8425 (Universal Resort station will operate synchronously with the opening of [[Universal Beijing Resort]].)}}</ref>\n| 1\n|}\n\n==Future Development==\n===Through operations with Line 1===\nIn 2010, a CPPCC member Chen Dingwang, proposed that services on [[Line 1 (Beijing Subway)|Line 1]] and the Ba Tong Line should directly link, with [[Through train|through operations]], reducing travel times and removing the unnecessary forced transfers at Sihui East or Sihui.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.china.com.cn/economic/txt/2011-09/16/content_23426447.htm |script-title=zh:\u5317\u4eac\u5730\u94c1\u516b\u901a\u7ebf\u4e00\u53f7\u7ebf\u6709\u671b\u8d2f\u901a |publisher=\u4e2d\u56fd\u7f51 |date=2011-09-16}}</ref> However, the [[Beijing Subway]] responded that Line 1's and Ba Tong's [[Railway signalling|signal]] systems are completely different, so through-operation will be more difficult to achieve, from an engineering standpoint. As of 2016, preliminary design and feasibility studies are underway to allow for through operations between Line 1 and Ba Tong.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://finance.qianlong.com/2016/1114/1109977.shtml |script-title=zh:\u5317\u4eac\u516b\u901a\u7ebf\u5357\u5ef6\u5de5\u7a0b\u521d\u6b65\u8bbe\u8ba1\u987a\u5229\u901a\u8fc7\u8bc4\u5ba1-\u5343\u9f99\u7f51\u00b7\u4e2d\u56fd\u9996\u90fd\u7f51|website=finance.qianlong.com|access-date=2016-11-17}}</ref> Work has begin through operation with Line 1 in conjunction with signal upgrades to allow trains to run every two minutes just like Line 1. Completion of this project is scheduled for 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://liuyan.people.com.cn/threads/content?tid=6072229|title=\u5730\u94c1\u516b\u901a\u7ebf\u95ee\u9898|date=2019-06-28|accessdate=2019-12-04}}</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Batong Line, Beijing Subway}}\n{{commons|Beijing Subway}}\n\n{{Beijing transit}}\n{{Beijing Subway Station\n|Batong=yes\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Batong Line}}\n[[Category:Beijing Subway lines]]\n[[Category:Railway lines opened in 2003]]\n[[Category:Standard gauge railways in China]]\n[[Category:750 V DC railway electrification]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox rail line\n| name                            = \n| other_name                      = M1 East (planned name)<br>Line 1 East<br>Line BT\n| logo                            = {{huge|{{rint|beijing|b}}}}\n| logo_width                      = \n| color                           = {{BJS color|b}}\n| image                           = Guoyuan station platform.jpg\n| image_width                     = 265px\n| image_alt                       = \n| caption                         = \n| type                            = [[Rapid transit]]\n| system                          = [[Beijing Subway]]\n| status                          = Operational\n| locale                          = [[Tongzhou District, Beijing|Tongzhou]] and [[Chaoyang District, Beijing|Chaoyang]] districts<br/>[[Beijing]]\n| start                           = {{BJS stations|Sihui}}\n| end                             = {{BJS stations|Huazhuang}}\n| stations                        = 14\n| routes                          = \n| daily_ridership                 = \n| ridership2                      = 300,600 (2014 Avg.)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bjsubway.com/node/3194|title=Official Ridership|publisher=Beijing Subway|accessdate=2013-03-10|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130322011003/http://www.bjsubway.com/node/3194|archivedate=2013-03-22}}</ref> <br> 364,800 (2014 Peak)\n| open                            = {{start date and age|2003|12|27}}\n| close                           = \n| owner                           = \n| operator                        = [[Beijing Mass Transit Railway Operation Corporation Limited|Beijing Mass Transit Railway Operation Corp., Ltd]]\n| character                       = Elevated, at-grade, underground\n| depot                           = Sihui, Tuqiao<ref>{{cite book |script-title=zh:\u5317\u4eac\u5730\u94c1\u516b\u901a\u7ebf\u52d8\u5bdf\u8bbe\u8ba1\u00b7\u65bd\u5de5\u76d1\u7406\u00b7\u5efa\u8bbe\u7ba1\u7406 |author1=Liu Hongtao (\u5218\u6d2a\u6d9b) |editor=Song Minhua ({{lang|zh-hans|\u5b8b\u654f\u534e}}) |location=Beijing |publisher=\u4e2d\u56fd\u5efa\u7b51\u5de5\u4e1a\u51fa\u7248\u793e |year=2008|pages=314\u2013325|isbn=978-7-112-09808-8}}</ref>\n| stock                           = 6-car Type B (SFM01, SFM02, SFM07, BDK06)\n| linelength                      = {{convert|23.4|km|abbr=on}}<ref name=qianlong20191218>{{cite web|url=http://beijing.qianlong.com/2019/1218/3467046.shtml|title=\u5317\u4eac\u5730\u94c17\u53f7\u7ebf\u4e1c\u5ef6\u548c\u516b\u901a\u7ebf\u5357\u5ef6\u4eca\u5e74\u5e95\u5f00\u901a\u8bd5\u8fd0\u8425}}</ref>\n| tracklength                     = \n| tracks                          = \n| gauge                           = {{track gauge|sg|allk=on}}\n| electrification                 = [[Third rail]]\n| speed                           = \n| elevation                       = \n| website                         = \n| map                             = {{Beijing Subway/Batong}}\n| map_state                       = collapsed\n}}\nThe '''Ba Tong Line''' of the [[Beijing Subway]] ({{zh|s=\u5317\u4eac\u5730\u94c1\u516b\u901a\u7ebf|p=b\u011bij\u012bng d\u00ecti\u011b b\u0101t\u014dng xi\u00e0n}}) is an east-west [[rapid transit]] line in eastern [[Beijing]]. It extends [[Line 1 (Beijing Subway)|Line 1]] further east from {{BJS stations|Sihui}} in [[Chaoyang District, Beijing|Chaoyang District]] to {{BJS stations|Huazhuang}} in [[Tongzhou District, Beijing|Tongzhou District]].\n\nThe Ba Tong Line derives its name by combining the first character of '''Ba'''wangfen ({{lang|zh-hans|\u516b\u738b\u575f}}), another name for Sihui, and '''Tong'''zhou ({{lang|zh|\u901a\u5dde}}), the eastern suburban district of Beijing which the line serves.\n\nThe Ba Tong Line is mainly above ground with only 3.8 km section is underground<ref name=bj2018-12-15>{{cite web|url=http://bj.people.com.cn/n2/2018/1215/c82840-32413471.html|date=2018-12-15|title=\u901a\u5dde\u4e09\u7ebf\u6362\u4e58\u65bd\u56ed\u7ad9\u5c01\u9876 \u516b\u901a\u7ebf\u5357\u5ef67\u53f7\u7ebf\u4e1c\u5ef6\u660e\u5e74\u5e95\u5f00\u901a}}</ref> and runs {{convert|23.4|km|abbr=on}}<ref name=qianlong20191218 /> from the {{BJS stations|Sihui}} in the west to {{BJS stations|Huazhuang}} in the east. The colour of Ba Tong Line that is shown on maps, like that of [[Line 1 (Beijing Subway)|Line 1]], is red.\n\nSince, aside from [[Line 6 (Beijing Subway)|Line 6]], the Ba Tong Line is the only subway line serving Tongzhou and eastern Chaoyang Districts, it tends be very crowded during rush hour. To alleviate this headways were reduced and [[skip-stop]] services were introduced during rush hour. \n\n==Fare==\nStarting fare of [[Renminbi|RMB(\u00a5)]] 3.00 that increases according to the distance fare scheme introduced in December 2014.\n\nRegular subway users can use a [[Yikatong]] card, which offers even cheaper journeys, as well as mobile phone apps, which deploy payment via a [[QR code]].\n\n==Hours of Operation==\nThe first east-bound train departs [[Sihui Station|Sihui]] at 6:00am. The first west-bound train departs Tuqiao at 5:20am. The last east-bound train leaves Sihui 10:45pm. The last west-bound train leaves Tuqiao at 10:05pm. For the official timetable, see [http://www.bjsubway.com/chinese_ver/cczn/TimeTableDetails.asp?TimeID=14].\n\n==Route==\nThe Ba Tong Line follows the [[Jingtong Expressway|Beijing-Tongzhou Expressway]] eastward from Sihui to Guanzhuang. Between [[Gaobeidian Station|Gaobeidian]] and [[Guanzhuang station (Batong line)|Guanzhuang]], the Ba Tong Line and its stations are built into the highway's median. At [[Baliqiao]], the Ba Tong Line turns to the southeast and follows the Jingtang Road to Tuqiao, which is located just inside the Tuqiao Bridge exit on the eastern [[6th Ring Road]].\n\n==Stations (from West to East)==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"margin:1em auto 1em left;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Station<br>No.\n! colspan=\"3\" |Service Route\n<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.bjsubway.com/station/xltcx/linebt/2013-08-20/36.html?sk=1|title=\u516b\u901a\u7ebf {{!}} \u5317\u4eac\u5730\u94c1\u5b98\u65b9\u7f51\u7ad9|website=www.bjsubway.com|access-date=2020-04-24}}</ref>\n! colspan=\"2\" | Station Name\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Connections\n! rowspan=\"2\" | [[Beijing Bus|Nearby Bus Stops]]\n! rowspan=\"2\" | Travel Time\n! colspan=\"2\" rowspan=\"2\" | Distance<br>{{