|\u25cf\n|style=\"background:lightgreen; text-align:center\"|\u25cf\n|{{BJS stations|Hua Zhuang}}\n|{{large|{{lang|zh-cn|\u82b1\u5e84}}}}\n|{{rint|beijing|7}}\n|\n|0:38\n|2.3\n|20.3\n|- bgcolor=\"lightgrey\"\n|style=\"background:#{{BJS color|Batong}}; color:white\"|\u2014{{efn|name=A|}}\n|\n|\n|\n|''{{BJS stations|Universal Resort}}''\n|{{large|{{lang|zh-cn|\u73af\u7403\u5ea6\u5047\u533a}}}}\n|{{rint|beijing|7}}\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|- style = \"background:#{{BJS color|Batong}}; height: 2pt\"\n| colspan=\"12\" |\n|}\n{{notelist}}\n\n[[Image:\u5317\u4eac\u516b\u901a\u7dda\u5217\u8eca\u8eca\u982d.JPG|thumb|180px|right|A Batong Line train at Sihui]]\n[[File:Beijing Subway Gaobeidian LineBT.jpg|thumb|180px|[[Gaobeidian station]] on the Ba Tong Line is located in the median of the [[Jingtong Expressway|Beijing-Tongzhou Expressway]]]]\n\n==Rolling stock==\n{{main|Beijing Subway Rolling Stock}}\n\nThe line uses 6-car Type B rolling stock.\n\n===Current===\n*[[Beijing Subway SFM01/07 train|SFM01 trainsets]] #TQ401-TQ408, #TQ414-TQ424\n*[[Beijing Subway SFM02 train|SFM02 trainsets]] #TQ409-TQ413\n*[[Beijing Subway SFM01/07 train|SFM07 trainsets]] #TQ425-TQ430\n*[[Beijing Subway BDK06 train|BDK06 trainsets]] #TQ431-TQ437\n\n===Former===\n*[[Beijing Subway DK3 train|DK3 trainsets]] #TQ101-TQ114\n*[[Beijing Subway DK16 train|DK16 trainsets]] #TQ115-TQ118\n\n==History==\n===Phase 1===\nConstruction of the Ba Tong Line began on December 28, 2001 and the line opened on December 27, 2003.\n\nIn 2012, traffic on Ba Tong Line was relieved by the opening of the parallel [[Line 6, Beijing Subway|Line 6]], with a 12.14% decrease in daily ridership and a 10\u201320% reduction in flow during rush hour.<ref name=\"ridership\">{{cite news|url=http://www.bjjtw.gov.cn/gzdt/ywsds/201302/t20130207_71407.htm |script-title=zh:\u6211\u5e02\u8f68\u9053\u4ea4\u901a\u7f51\u7edc\u5316\u8fd0\u8425\u6548\u679c\u51f8\u663e|date=2013-02-07|accessdate=2013-09-15|publisher=\u5317\u4eac\u5e02\u4ea4\u901a\u59d4\u5458\u4f1a [Beijing Municipal Transportation Committee] |url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140109144501/http://www.bjjtw.gov.cn/gzdt/ywsds/201302/t20130207_71407.htm|archivedate=2014-01-09}}</ref> However, during peak hours sections the line still operates above 100% capacity.<ref name = \"ridership\"/>\n\n===Southern extension (Phase 2)===\nThere are 2 stations on the southern extension: {{BJS stations|Huazhuang}} station and {{BJS stations|Universal Resort}} station (both are transfer stations with the eastern extension of [[Line 7 (Beijing Subway)|Line 7]]).<ref>http://www.xinhuanet.com/local/2018-12/15/c_1123856864.htm</ref> The extension is 4.5&nbsp;km in length,<ref name=bj2019length>{{cite web|url=http://www.bjnews.com.cn/feature/2019/09/10/624954.html|title=\u5730\u94c17\u53f7\u7ebf\u4e1c\u5ef6\u3001\u516b\u901a\u7ebf\u5357\u5ef6\u4eca\u65e5\u8bd5\u8fd0\u884c \u5e74\u5e95\u5f00\u901a|date=2019-09-10}}</ref> including 3.8&nbsp;km underground section.<ref name=bj20181215>http://bj.people.com.cn/n2/2018/1215/c82840-32413471.html</ref> {{BJS stations|Huazhuang}} station was opened on December 28, 2019.<ref name=bjd-1/> {{BJS stations|Universal Resort}} station will open simultaneously with the opening of [[Universal Beijing Resort]]<ref name=bjd-0 /> (in May 2021<ref name=\"news202002\">{{Cite web|url=http://news.ifeng.com/c/7u78Lx2rAEY|title=\u5317\u4eac\u73af\u7403\u4e3b\u9898\u516c\u56ed\u660e\u5e745\u6708\u5f00\u56ed|date=2020-02-16|accessdate=2020-02-17}}</ref>).\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" cellpadding=\"3\" style=\"border-collapse: collapse; text-align: right;\"\n!Segment!!Commencement!!Length!!Station(s)!!Name\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"| Sihui \u2014 Tuqiao\n| 27 December 2003\n| {{convert|18.964|km|mi|1|abbr=on}}<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.sina.com.cn/o/2003-05-29/2023169473s.shtml|date=2003-05-29|title=\u5317\u4eac\u5730\u94c1\u516b\u901a\u7ebf\u8f68\u9053\u5168\u7ebf\u8d2f\u901a \u4ecd\u5c06\u786e\u4fdd\u5e74\u5e95\u901a\u8f66}}</ref>\n| 13\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"| Phase 1\n|-\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"| Tuqiao \u2014 Hua Zhuang\n| 28 December 2019<ref name=bjd-1>{{cite web|url=http://bjwb.bjd.com.cn/html/2019-12/25/content_12438029.htm|title=7\u53f7\u7ebf\u4e1c\u5ef6\u516b\u901a\u7ebf\u5357\u5ef6\u672c\u5468\u516d\u5f00\u901a\u8bd5\u8fd0\u8425 \u8fd0\u8425\u65f6\u95f4\u4fdd\u6301\u4e0d\u53d8 \u73af\u7403\u5ea6\u5047\u533a\u7ad9\u6682\u4e0d\u5f00\u901a|date=2019-12-25}}</ref>\n|rowspan=\"2\"|{{convert|4.5|km|mi|abbr=on}}<ref name=bj2019length />\n| 1\n|rowspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align: left;\"| Phase 2 (Southern extension)\n|-bgcolor=\"lightgrey\"\n|style=\"text-align: left;\"| Hua Zhuang \u2014 Universal Resort\n| 2021 (Planned)<ref name=bjd-0>{{cite web|url=http://www.bjd.com.cn/a/201912/24/WS5e01d31ce4b0e6e58393462e.html|title=\u5730\u94c17\u53f7\u7ebf\u4e1c\u5ef6\u3001\u516b\u901a\u7ebf\u5357\u5ef6\u5c06\u4e8e\u5e74\u5e95\u5f00\u901a\u8bd5\u8fd0\u8425|date=2019-12-24|quote=\u73af\u7403\u5ea6\u5047\u533a\u7ad9\u5c06\u968f\u73af\u7403\u5ea6\u5047\u533a\u5f00\u653e\u540c\u6b65\u8fd0\u8425 (Universal Resort station will operate synchronously with the opening of [[Universal Beijing Resort]].)}}</ref>\n| 1\n|}\n\n==Future Development==\n===Through operations with Line 1===\nIn 2010, a CPPCC member Chen Dingwang, proposed that services on [[Line 1 (Beijing Subway)|Line 1]] and the Ba Tong Line should directly link, with [[Through train|through operations]], reducing travel times and removing the unnecessary forced transfers at Sihui East or Sihui.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.china.com.cn/economic/txt/2011-09/16/content_23426447.htm |script-title=zh:\u5317\u4eac\u5730\u94c1\u516b\u901a\u7ebf\u4e00\u53f7\u7ebf\u6709\u671b\u8d2f\u901a |publisher=\u4e2d\u56fd\u7f51 |date=2011-09-16}}</ref> However, the [[Beijing Subway]] responded that Line 1's and Ba Tong's [[Railway signalling|signal]] systems are completely different, so through-operation will be more difficult to achieve, from an engineering standpoint. As of 2016, preliminary design and feasibility studies are underway to allow for through operations between Line 1 and Ba Tong.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://finance.qianlong.com/2016/1114/1109977.shtml |script-title=zh:\u5317\u4eac\u516b\u901a\u7ebf\u5357\u5ef6\u5de5\u7a0b\u521d\u6b65\u8bbe\u8ba1\u987a\u5229\u901a\u8fc7\u8bc4\u5ba1-\u5343\u9f99\u7f51\u00b7\u4e2d\u56fd\u9996\u90fd\u7f51|website=finance.qianlong.com|access-date=2016-11-17}}</ref> Work has begin through operation with Line 1 in conjunction with signal upgrades to allow trains to run every two minutes just like Line 1. Completion of this project is scheduled for 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://liuyan.people.com.cn/threads/content?tid=6072229|title=\u5730\u94c1\u516b\u901a\u7ebf\u95ee\u9898|date=2019-06-28|accessdate=2019-12-04}}</ref> \n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Batong Line, Beijing Subway}}\n{{commons|Beijing Subway}}\n\n{{Beijing transit}}\n{{Beijing Subway}}\n{{Beijing Subway Station\n|Batong=yes\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Batong Line}}\n[[Category:Beijing Subway lines]]\n[[Category:Railway lines opened in 2003]]\n[[Category:Standard gauge railways in China]]\n[[Category:750 V DC railway electrification]]\n", "name_user": "Terramorphous", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ba_Tong_line"}
{"title_page": "Dime Store Cowgirl", "text_new": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Dime Store Cowgirl\n| cover      = File:Kacey Musgraves - Dime Store Cowgirl.jpg\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Kacey Musgraves]]\n| album      = [[Pageant Material]]\n| released   = {{Start date|2015|8|3}}\n| format     = [[Music download|Digital download]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Country music|Country]]\n| length     = {{duration|m=3|s=35}}\n| label      = [[Mercury Nashville]]\n| writer     = {{flatlist|\n*Kacey Musgraves\n*[[Luke Laird]]\n*[[Shane McAnally]]\n}}\n| producer   = {{flatlist|\n*Kacey Musgraves\n*Luke Laird\n*Shane McAnally\n}}\n| prev_title = [[Biscuits (song)|Biscuits]]\n| prev_year  = 2015\n| next_title = [[Space Cowboy (Kacey Musgraves song)|Space Cowboy]]\n| next_year  = 2018\n}}\n\n\"'''Dime Store Cowgirl'''\" is a song recorded by American [[country music]] artist [[Kacey Musgraves]] that serves as the second single from her second major label studio album, ''[[Pageant Material]]''. It was released to country radio on August 3, 2015, through [[Mercury Nashville]]. The song was written and produced by Musgraves with [[Luke Laird]] and [[Shane McAnally]]. The song was nominated for \"Song of the Year\" at the 2016 [[Americana Music Honors & Awards]].\n\n==Lyrical interpretation==\nIn lyrics of the song, Musgraves sings \"''slept in a room with the ghost of [[Gram Parsons]].''\" Musgraves has elaborated on the meaning of this lyric, saying that she has stayed at \"the infamous Joshua Tree Inn\" Motel, in California\" several times, including filming the video for [[Follow Your Arrow]] there. The motel is where 27-year-old singer-songwriter Parsons [[Death of Gram Parsons|died of an overdose in 1973]]. The motel is rumored to be haunted, and Musgraves has said that she felt she had paranormal experiences, such as objects moving/art taken down off the wall.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://exclaim.ca/amparticle/kacey_musgraves_recounts_her_encounter_with_gram_parsons_ghost |title= Kacey Musgraves Recounts Her Encounter with Gram Parsons' Ghost |date=June 23, 2015 |accessdate=May 22, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://mobile.nytimes.com/2015/09/10/t-magazine/gram-parsons-joshua-tree-inn.amp.html |title=A Joshua Tree Motel Room, Haunted by the Ghost of a Country Legend |date=September 10, 2015 |accessdate=May 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n===Accolades===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Publication\n! Rank\n! List\n|-Ad\n| RoughStock\n| align=center| 3\n| The Top 30 Singles of 2015<ref name=\"RoughStockbestsongsof2015\">{{cite web|url=http://roughstock.com/news/2016/01/39545-the-top-30-singles-of-2015|title=The Top 30 Singles of 2015|author=Matt Bjorke|date=January 2, 2016|work=RoughStock|accessdate=January 3, 2016}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Association\n! Category\n! Result\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|2016\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[Americana Music Honors & Awards]]<ref name=\"2016AMHAnom\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tennessean.com/story/entertainment/music/2016/09/21/2016-americana-music-honors-and-awards-show-kicks-off-ryman/90794618/|first=Juli|last=Thanki|title=Isbell takes home Album, Song of the Year Americana Awards|work=The Tennessean|date=September 22, 2016|accessdate=September 22, 2016}}</ref>\n|Song of the Year\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n==Chart performance==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n! Chart (2015)\n! Peak <br/> position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardcountrysongs|44|artist=Kacey Musgraves}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Kacey Musgraves}}\n\n[[Category:2015 songs]]\n[[Category:2015 singles]]\n[[Category:Kacey Musgraves songs]]\n[[Category:Mercury Nashville singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Kacey Musgraves]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Luke Laird]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Shane McAnally]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Luke Laird]]\n[[Category:Song recordings produced by Shane McAnally]]\n\n\n{{2010s-country-song-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox song\n| name       = Dime Store Cowgirl\n| cover      = File:Kacey Musgraves - Dime Store Cowgirl.jpg\n| alt        =\n| border     = yes\n| type       = single\n| artist     = [[Kacey Musgraves]]\n| album      = [[Pageant Material]]\n| released   = {{Start date|2015|8|3}}\n| format     = [[Music download|Digital download]]\n| recorded   =\n| studio     =\n| venue      =\n| genre      = [[Country music|Country]]\n| length     = {{duration|m=3|s=35}}\n| label      = [[Mercury Nashville]]\n| writer     = {{flatlist|\n*Kacey Musgraves\n*[[Luke Laird]]\n*[[Shane McAnally]]\n}}\n| producer   = {{flatlist|\n*Kacey Musgraves\n*Luke Laird\n*Shane McAnally\n}}\n| prev_title = [[Biscuits (song)|Biscuits]]\n| prev_year  = 2015\n| next_title = [[Space Cowboy (Kacey Musgraves song)|Space Cowboy]]\n| next_year  = 2018\n}}\n\n\"'''Dime Store Cowgirl'''\" is a song recorded by American [[country music]] artist [[Kacey Musgraves]] that serves as the second single from her second major label studio album, ''[[Pageant Material]]''. It was released to country radio on August 3, 2015, through [[Mercury Nashville]]. The song was written and produced by Musgraves with [[Luke Laird]] and [[Shane McAnally]]. The song was nominated for \"Song of the Year\" at the 2016 [[Americana Music Honors & Awards]].\n\n==Lyrical interpretation==\nIn lyrics of the song, Musgraves sings \"''slept in a room with the ghost of [[Gram Parsons]].''\" Musgraves has elaborated on the meaning of this lyric, saying that she has stayed at \"the infamous Joshua Tree Inn\" Motel, in California\" several times, including filming the video for [[Follow Your Arrow]] there. The motel is where 27-year-old singer-songwriter Parsons [[Death of Gram Parsons|died of an overdose in 1973]]. The motel is rumored to be haunted, and Musgraves has said that she felt she had paranormal experiences, such as objects moving/art taken down off the wall.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://exclaim.ca/amparticle/kacey_musgraves_recounts_her_encounter_with_gram_parsons_ghost |title= Kacey Musgraves Recounts Her Encounter with Gram Parsons' Ghost |date=June 23, 2015 |accessdate=May 22, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url= https://mobile.nytimes.com/2015/09/10/t-magazine/gram-parsons-joshua-tree-inn.amp.html |title=A Joshua Tree Motel Room, Haunted by the Ghost of a Country Legend |date=September 10, 2015 |accessdate=May 22, 2018}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n===Accolades===\n{|class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Publication\n! Rank\n! List\n|-Ad\n| RoughStock\n| align=center| 3\n| The Top 30 Singles of 2015<ref name=\"RoughStockbestsongsof2015\">{{cite web|url=http://roughstock.com/news/2016/01/39545-the-top-30-singles-of-2015|title=The Top 30 Singles of 2015|author=Matt Bjorke|date=January 2, 2016|work=RoughStock|accessdate=January 3, 2016}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Association\n! Category\n! Result\n|-\n|rowspan=\"1\"|2016\n|rowspan=\"1\"|[[Americana Music Honors & Awards]]<ref name=\"2016AMHAnom\">{{cite web|url=http://www.tennessean.com/story/entertainment/music/2016/09/21/2016-americana-music-honors-and-awards-show-kicks-off-ryman/90794618/|first=Juli|last=Thanki|title=Isbell takes home Album, Song of the Year Americana Awards|work=The Tennessean|date=September 22, 2016|accessdate=September 22, 2016}}</ref>\n|Song of the Year\n| {{nom}}\n|}\n\n==Chart performance==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Chart (2015)\n! Peak <br/> position\n|-\n{{singlechart|Billboardcountrysongs|44|artist=Kacey Musgraves}}\n|-\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Kacey Musgraves}}\n\n[[Category:2015 songs]]\n[[Category:2015 singles]]\n[[Category:Kacey Musgraves songs]]\n[[Category:Mercury Nashville singles]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Kacey Musgraves]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Luke Laird]]\n[[Category:Songs written by Shane McAnally]]\n[[Category:Song reco